prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 7 continuum
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We propose to measure dust continuum emission for 223 young stars in the 0.5-Myr-old Orion NGC 2024 cluster in order to determine disk masses and constrain disk evolution in young clusters.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We will also target the CO J=3-2, HCN J=4-3, HCO+ J=4-3, and CS J=7-6 lines. The expected line widths are ~3-10 km/s, so we will use a channel spacing of 0.244 MHz, which will be Hanning smoothed and spectrally averaged (N=4) to a spectral resolution of 0.8 km/s. The resolution is similar to that used in Cycle 0/1 observations of the Orion Nebula disks, which clearly revealed Keplerian velocity gradients in several disks (see Figure 3; Williams et al. 2014).

We request 0.5" FWHM resolution to distinguish individual disks, which are clustered together near the O-star, IRS2b in NGC 2024 (see Figure 1), and to resolve the dust-disk emission for the largest disks in the region. The largest angular size is based on the 2.5" resolution of our previous SMA observations.

We request observations with ALMA using its Band 7 (870 micron) receivers to measure the dust and gas in protoplanetary disks around 233 young stars in the NGC 2024 cluster. We will survey 100 pointings to a depth of 1-sigma ~ 0.25 mJy/beam (3-sigma ~ 0.3 Mjup), which can be achieved in 1.6 minutes per pointing (2.7 hours on-source) as calculated by the ALMA OT, using 2nd octile weather conditions.
Our proposed RMS of 0.25 mJy corresponds to a 3-sigma mass sensitivity of 0.3 Mjup, which, as mentioned in the scientific justification, will allow us to detect masses comparable to the Cycle 0/1 observations of the Orion Nebula cluster and reveal the full disk mass distribution in NGC 2024. The ability to detect sub-Jupiter mass disks is essential in rich clusters like NGC 2024, as theoretical models predict disks are rapidly photoevaporated to small sizes and masses if they are located near O-stars due to the extreme-UV radiation (Johnstone et al. 1998, Adams et al. 2004).
Diameters of the target disks likely range from 0.1 arcsec - 2.5 arcsec (the resolution of our previous SMA observations), or 40-1000 AU at 400pc, the distance to NGC 2024. If a typical 20 K Taurus disk was placed at the distance of NGC 2024 in a 0.5" beam, an an appropriate beam filling factor was applied, the observed line temperatures would range between 1.3 K to 20 K. The ALMA sensitivity calculator estimates an rms noise temperature of 1.3 K for these observations, which is sufficient to detect even cold molecular gas in these disks.
Our requested observational setup is identical to our Cycle 0/1 projects in the Orion Nebula cluster, which will allow us to probe the same spatial scales, to a similar depth and at the same observing frequency. These observations cannot be carried out at lower frequencies as the ionized gas surrounding photoevaporating disks in high-mass star-forming regions can swamp the thermal dust emission from disks even at 1.3-mm (Mann & Williams, 2009).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to survey 233 protoplanetary disks in the 0.5-Myr-old NGC 2024 cluster with ALMA, in order to measure their masses, sizes and gas content. NGC 2024 is a particularly compelling target because it is a young, high-mass star-forming region which has the highest suspected disk fraction reported to date, making it an ideal region to study the initial conditions of planet formation. With these observations, NGC 2024 will be the youngest cluster for which the full disk mass distribution is known, knowledge of which will have immediate implications for disk evolution as disk properties are poorly constrained for ages < 1 Myr. By comparison with disk properties in older clusters, we will be able to track disk evolution and thereby constrain planet formation timescales. Furthermore, by observing a large number of young disks in a more primitive state than have previously been observed, we will be able to determine more realistically if all stars are born with disks, and their potential to form planetary systems like our own.
